{
  "text": "The relation (3) can be used to estimate speed in derived titanosaurs, such as the Titanopodus trackmakers, following the general equation of Alexander (equation 1). The results are shown in Table I . According to this analysis, the Titanopodus tracks were produced by medium-sized titanosaurs. Sizes and anatomical proportions are estimated in based on the equation 3 and ichnological data. Trackways AC-1 and AC-4 were produced by sauropod specimens that had a hip height (H ) of 211 cm and 229 cm, respectively (Fig. 5) . The ratio of glenoacetabular distance to hip joint height (G AD/H ) is useful for estimating the body length and relative anatomical proportions. According to [CITATION_1] , the ratio G AD/H of sauropods shows values that range from 0.97 to 1.26, with an average of 1.09.",
  "citation_candidates": [
